elvetica, sans-serif; COLOR: #000; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Namaste friends,  =
 Bhakti yoga or the path of surrender and devotion is indeed more suitable =
in this age. I did not mean to say otherwise.   But just having an ish=
ta devata is not enough to be "protected" from deep and troublesome instabi=
lities when one's body-mind complex goes through a big transformation. Not =
every aspiring devotee becomes a Prahlada - some become Ravanas. After all,=
 out of the two examples Leelaji gave below for "psychological disorder", t=
he second lady "did much sadhana of Srirama". Even those who think of a dei=
ty and pray to him/her can end up with hallucinations, mental and spiritual=
 disorders, wrong (colored by one's conditioning and desires!) interpretati=
on of internal/external experiences and even madness.   True surrender=
/devotion to ishta devata will definitely protect one, but cultivating it i=
s as
 difficult as cultivating detachment through wisdom! In fact, true sur=
render and detachment are almost the same.   This is why I said that *=
lightness of conditioning* is the most important thing. One with dense cond=
itioning will find SOME way to fail even if a great guru or god are ready t=
o help.   *        *  &nb=
sp;     *   Now, the question is: How do we reduce=
 our conditioning? Unfortunately, there is no single magic bullet. Thinking=
 of a god, mantras, bhajans, japam, homam etc can help, but they need to be=
 augmented by regular introspection and self-improvement.   Taking min=
d away from its current pre-occupations (e.g. "I am smart", "I am doing goo=
d sadhana", "I am mad at X", "I did not get what I deserve in Y", "I am bet=
ter than X", "I must have Y at any cost" etc etc) is key to eventually over=
coming conditioning, for these thoughts keep *reinforcing* the
 conditionin=
g!   To reduce the regular pre-occupations of mind, different imagery/=
visualization may work better for some people.   One approach is to co=
ntemplate god whenever possible, in the middle of any activity. You can ima=
gine a being in your mind, either as an ideal/able person or as a principle=
/ideal/ability that exists in many beings, that is so perfect and fascinati=
ng for the mind to contemplate that it does not care about other objects ar=
ound that are making shadripus and ashtapashas work on the mind. Whenever m=
ind is about to entertain its regular debilitating pre-occupations, one can=
 try to contemplate god instead.   Mind is a wild animal. As Pi says i=
n the movie "Life of Pi" about the tiger on the boat, wild animals can't be=
 transformed or domesticated, but they can be trained into some habits! &nb=
sp; Whenever one is enjoying a sensual pleasure, if one thinks "the omnipre=
sent God is enjoying this thru this instrument" and
 starts contemplating t=
he qualities of that god instead of thinking too much about limited sense o=
bjects, one is better placed to reduce the damage done by shadripus. Whenev=
er one is angry at someone for what they did, if one thinks "the omnipresen=
t God is giving me the fruits of my karmas thru that instrument" and starts=
 contemplating the qualities of that god instead of being angry at someone,=
 one is better placed to reduce the damage done by shadripus. And so on. &n=
bsp; In the beginning, even contemplation of god becomes laced with ego. Ev=
ery now and then, the activity ends up becoming about oneself rather than a=
bout god ("*I* am doing this nice bhajan", "*I* am doing this nice homam", =
"I think *I* am making progress through this"). With effort and perseveranc=
e, one can avoid making it about oneself and keep it centered on the suprem=
e power that runs the show. Just as it takes a long time to train a wild an=
imal, it takes a long time to train mind!
   Try to develop devotion a=
nd surrender. Based on all that you read and heard, develop of a concept/pr=
inciple of god that is so superb and fascinarting. Visualize/contemplate th=
at concept as frequently as possible, especially when meditating. When mind=
 veers off into other things, gently steer it back. Don't spend too much ti=
me dissecting what mind is doing and why. Just put it back gently into cont=
emplating god. Try to make it about god rather than about yourself.   =
The main drawback of the sadhana of most people is that they make it about =
themselves at some level or the other. Though that is unavoidable, try to b=
reak free from it.   *        *&nbs=
p;       *   Finally, one can try to ove=
rcome the limited sense of self and engage in selfless actions that benefit=
 a larger set of people than oneself. What stops us from truly loving god i=
s our deep and sub-conscious love
 for *ourselves* (i.e. our *limited* noti=
on of self that drives the current body-mind complex). One way to overcome =
that is to selflessly love others. After all, other people around us are as=
 much replicas of god as we are. If we cannot empathize with them, love the=
m and give them unconditionally, how can we ever hope to transcend the limi=
