_1362067846619_141>Namaste friends,<BR> <BR>Someone with psychiatric p=
roblems may expereience what sounds like a Kundalini rise, but it may or ma=
y not be one.<BR> <BR>It must be conceded though that Kundalini sponta=
neously rising through various nadis without one having gone through proper=
 preparation in this life (i.e. fine-tuning of one's attitude and developme=
nt of detachment) CAN create havoc!<BR> <BR>One may wonder how Kundali=
ni may spontaneously rise in a layman with no sadhana, while many serious s=
adhakas may not experience it.<BR> <BR>Firstly, Kundalini rise is NOT =
an achievement. It is just A SMALL STEP in overcoming one's current limited=
 identity.<BR> <BR>Let me give an analogy. One wanting to move from on=
e's small dilapidated house (this body-mind complex) to a huge palace (real=
ized Self) may first construct the palace over time and
 move into it when =
it is COMPLETE. Alternately, if one occasionally goes and stays in the pala=
ce still under construction (analogy for out of body experiences due to Kun=
dalini rise), is it an achievement? In fact, it comes with risks. The forme=
r approach is safer and one loses nothing in it. Similarly, one can progres=
s towards complete Self-realization without any out of body experiences. Th=
ese are not my word's, but Maharshi Vasishtha's words to Lord Rama.<BR>&nbs=
p;<BR>Secondly, one does not get something without wanting it and putting s=
ufficient effort towards it. One may have deeply desired a Kundalini rise i=
n a previous life and may have put enough effort. As a result, one may be g=
etting it now. But one may be unprepared (and ironically may not even want =
it!) when it comes in this life.<BR> <BR>As you do sadhana, try not to=
 fancy too many specific desires. Nature has a delay mechanism in granting =
your desires (because of constraints on what
 Nature can give you right now=
, arising from YOUR OWN previous actions). So Nature sometimes gives you wh=
at you want LATE, when you no longer want it or want something else. For ex=
ample, one may pray for great wealth one's whole life and be born as a rich=
 but very sick man in next life. One may not enjoy that wealth and pray who=
le life for health. In the life after that, one may be very healthy, but no=
t have any knowledge or money. </SPAN><SPAN id=3Dyiv1685536178yui_3_7_2_19_=
1362067846619_141>In another case, one may deeply desire to act in a famous=
 film. One may be reborn as a tiger or a dog and act in a famous film, but =
not really enjoy that experience. Basically, people </SPAN><SPAN id=3Dyiv16=
85536178yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_141>keep going in circles through variou=
s lives, always "seeking" something they are "missing".<BR> <BR>Anyway=
, coming back to Kundalini, if one deeply desires an out of body experience=
 given by a rising Kundalini and one's
 previous karmas constrain one from =
having it in THIS life, one may be born in next life with this specific des=
ire destined to fructify (if there is enough karmik force behind it).<BR>&n=
bsp;<BR>*        *   &nbs=
p;    *<BR> <BR>Kundalini rise is not necessarily scary=
 or painful, if one is well-prepared in terms of attitude and detachment.<B=
R> <BR>Once I saw a chipmunk glued to a mouse trap. I went to free it =
and it panicked so badly and started to shake violently. I went to save it =
from a certain slow death and it was scared that I would kill it!<BR> =
<BR>We are like that chipmunk, glued to the mouse trap called this body-min=
d complex and scared of being rescued from a certain slow death!<BR> <=
BR>If our ideas about who we are (viz this current body-mind complex) are i=
ncorrect and if we are this "infinite Self" as shastras say, won't a comple=
te realization of that at some
 stage involve stepping out of this body-min=
d complex, without being scared?<BR> <BR>*    &nbs=
p;   *        *<BR> <BR>K=
undalini rise after most undesirable conditioning is overcome, is far bette=
r than Kundalini rise forced when some really undesirable conditioning is s=
till left in one's system.<BR> <BR>When one transcends one problematic=
 notion about who one is and what one needs, another notion that lay buried=
 deeper in consciousness may spring to the surface and torment one. If one =
overcomes the notion "I am the body", there may be another notion in one's =
body-mind complex that one's awareness clings on to (</SPAN><SPAN id=3Dyiv1=
685536178yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_141><SPAN class=3Dyiv1685536178userCont=
ent>e.g. a great doctor, a great leader, a great scholar, a great saint etc=
</SPAN>). As an extreme example, if one person had a hidden deep desire to =
be a great soul who rescues
 the world, he may fancy that he is a re-incarn=
ated X or Y who will rescue the world now. When one's self-awareness (i.e. =
Kundalini!) deeply clings to any such notion, it can cause havoc. The perso=
n may show some signs of progress and yet remain in ignorance and get stuck=
 badly.<BR> <BR>An awakened Kundalini in a system with undesirable con=
ditioning may accentuate one's weaknesses and wrong notions heavily and cau=
se serious psychiatric and spiritual problems.<BR> <BR>*  &n=
bsp;     *        *<=
BR> <BR id=3Dyiv1685536178yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_158>The best appr=
oach I recommend is to NOT think in terms of Kundalini and its rise. Just d=
o sadhana, overcome your weaknesses and improve your detachment over time. =
Again, I want to emphasize that detachment is not disgust or distaste for l=
ife/things/people around you. Disgust is the other side of coin of attachme=
nt.</SPAN> It is a
 negative attachment.  </DIV>
